WEBVTT

00:01.001 --> 00:03.003
[indistinct chatter]

00:05.672 --> 00:07.674
Mr. Suero?

00:08.675 --> 00:11.678
[dramatic music plays]

00:16.558 --> 00:18.227
[sighs]

00:20.687 --> 00:22.272
MILES:
Ah.

00:22.272 --> 00:25.275
Victor "Victory" Suero.

00:25.275 --> 00:26.777
Miles Sellars.

00:26.777 --> 00:29.321
Welcome to The Tiro Fund.
It's a true pleasure.

00:29.321 --> 00:30.906
I'm an admirer.

00:30.906 --> 00:32.282
Oh, you-you a fight fan?

00:32.282 --> 00:35.035
Yeah, I am. But a fan of yours
in particular.

00:35.035 --> 00:36.286
Have a seat.

00:36.286 --> 00:38.288
Really?
You specialize on fighters

00:38.288 --> 00:39.623
with sub-500 records?

00:39.623 --> 00:41.124
Oh, come on.

00:41.124 --> 00:43.877
You and I both know
that there are many reasons

00:43.877 --> 00:46.713
to admire you
outside your win-loss column.

00:46.713 --> 00:49.258
Your toughness, for example.

00:50.300 --> 00:51.802
When I was about, um...

00:51.802 --> 00:55.055
uh, around about 14,

00:55.055 --> 00:59.142
my old man brought us here
all the way from Austria.

01:00.561 --> 01:02.396
Looking for the American dream.

01:02.396 --> 01:04.815
And damn it if New York
didn't give it to him.

01:04.815 --> 01:06.984
[chuckles]

01:06.984 --> 01:10.779
He worked as a stevedore
in Red Hook.

01:10.779 --> 01:14.074
That toughened him up,
and as a result,

01:14.074 --> 01:15.951
he toughened us up.

01:15.951 --> 01:19.454
Me, my sisters, my brothers.

01:19.454 --> 01:20.956
You grow up in New York,

01:20.956 --> 01:23.625
and you take on the character
of the city.

01:23.625 --> 01:26.336
Stock market crash.

01:26.336 --> 01:28.463
Terrorist attacks.

01:28.463 --> 01:30.841
Blackout riots.

01:30.841 --> 01:32.259
Yeah.

01:32.259 --> 01:34.761
New York's a city that survives.

01:37.764 --> 01:39.224
That's how I knew

01:39.224 --> 01:41.476
that I could help you.

01:41.476 --> 01:43.145
I read up on you a little bit.

01:43.145 --> 01:45.606
You're a survivor, too,
aren't you, Victor?

01:45.606 --> 01:48.692
You survived a fire
that killed both your parents.

01:48.692 --> 01:51.820
You survived being bounced
from foster home to foster home,

01:51.820 --> 01:53.822
always protecting
your little sister.

01:53.822 --> 01:55.824
You survived
countless battles in the ring

01:55.824 --> 01:57.826
despite your affliction.

01:57.826 --> 02:00.787
[tense music plays]

02:02.831 --> 02:04.082
What is this?

02:04.082 --> 02:06.043
I assumed you train a lot

02:06.043 --> 02:10.088
and thought maybe you can use
a new pair of running shoes.

02:11.131 --> 02:13.383
You don't really
give out loans, do you?

02:13.383 --> 02:16.929
No. I do not.

02:16.929 --> 02:20.599
But let me tell you a little
about my line of work.

02:25.187 --> 02:29.066
<i>The hunt is 24 hours,
from sunrise to sunrise.</i>

02:29.066 --> 02:31.527
<i>$50,000 for the first hour,
$100,000 for the second.</i>

02:31.527 --> 02:34.905
<i>Deposits increase 50 grand
every hour</i>

02:34.905 --> 02:38.033
<i>until hour 20,
which pays a million.</i>

02:38.033 --> 02:39.785
<i>And that increases</i>

02:39.785 --> 02:42.871
<i>by a million every hour
after that for a total</i>

02:42.871 --> 02:45.123
<i>of $24.5 million.</i>

02:45.123 --> 02:48.085
<i>The game takes place in the
five boroughs and Long Island.</i>

02:48.085 --> 02:49.670
<i>Leave the confines,</i>

02:49.670 --> 02:52.923
<i>it's a violation,
and the game never ends.</i>

02:52.923 --> 02:55.801
<i>Tell anyone, it's a violation.
Go to the cops,</i>

02:55.801 --> 02:57.261
<i>get yourself arrested,
it's a violation.</i>

02:57.261 --> 02:59.263
<i>Top of every hour,
your location's</i>

02:59.263 --> 03:02.015
<i>given up to the hunters
for 15 seconds.</i>

03:02.015 --> 03:03.976
<i>You keep this phone on you
at all times,</i>

03:03.976 --> 03:05.686
<i>or it's a violation.</i>

03:05.686 --> 03:07.145
<i>No guns.</i>

03:07.145 --> 03:09.314
<i>Hunters need to get up close
and personal.</i>

03:09.314 --> 03:13.068
<i>Anyone you run into could be
the last person you ever see.</i>

03:13.068 --> 03:15.028
<i>Sport in its purest form,</i>

03:15.028 --> 03:17.781
<i>a hunt to kill.</i>

03:20.659 --> 03:22.286
$42,000.

03:22.286 --> 03:24.371
Down payment. Shows you
I can get you the money we owe.

03:24.371 --> 03:28.375
No. Shows me you can get me
less than ten percent

03:28.375 --> 03:30.627
- of money you owe.
- But I can get you the rest.

03:30.627 --> 03:32.504
We can work something out. Just...

03:32.504 --> 03:34.590
Just give me more time.

03:36.008 --> 03:38.552
The only thing
I'm going to give you...

03:39.595 --> 03:42.306
...is your little change purse back.

03:43.307 --> 03:46.351
You talk to those loan sharks
I told you about?

03:46.351 --> 03:48.187
You ever meet them?

03:48.187 --> 03:50.355
No, I have not.

03:50.355 --> 03:54.443
Because I have not made mistake
of owing when I cannot pay.

03:54.443 --> 03:56.528
So...

03:58.113 --> 04:00.449
Get loan.

04:00.449 --> 04:03.160
Rob bank. I don't give shit.

04:03.160 --> 04:04.703
But you walk in here

04:04.703 --> 04:06.580
with a less than full amount again,

04:06.580 --> 04:08.874
you don't walk out.

04:08.874 --> 04:10.918
But I promise you,

04:10.918 --> 04:12.794
I will stuff your sister

04:12.794 --> 04:15.339
in same oil drum I put you in

04:15.339 --> 04:18.258
so you can be together. Huh?

04:19.843 --> 04:21.512
Now go.

04:21.512 --> 04:23.555
Get me my money.

04:28.018 --> 04:31.021
<i>[door opens, closes]</i>
[siren wailing]

04:31.021 --> 04:32.689
JOSIE:

04:32.689 --> 04:34.149
Hey.

04:38.028 --> 04:39.112
Deli take you back?

04:39.112 --> 04:40.864
Yeah. They love me there.

04:46.870 --> 04:48.455
I need to show you something.

04:58.298 --> 05:01.301
["El Día de Mi Suerte"
by Héctor Lavoe playing]

05:02.344 --> 05:04.221
[chuckles]

05:09.601 --> 05:12.229
[singing in Spanish]

05:14.273 --> 05:15.691
VICTOR:
I looked it up.

05:16.733 --> 05:18.068
There's, like,

05:18.068 --> 05:21.363
12 decommissioned lighthouses
in the U.S. for sale.

05:21.363 --> 05:24.241
And they're expensive as shit, so...

05:25.409 --> 05:26.368
Probably won't be able

05:26.368 --> 05:27.953
- to afford you one.
- Boo.

05:27.953 --> 05:29.705
So...

05:29.705 --> 05:31.748
next best thing.

05:34.376 --> 05:36.211
I love it.

05:38.422 --> 05:40.424
[sighs]

05:41.842 --> 05:43.260
You're scared.

05:43.260 --> 05:45.095
How do you know?

05:45.095 --> 05:46.221
'Cause every time
you're scared,

05:46.221 --> 05:47.890
you do something like this.

05:49.474 --> 05:51.852
When you thought the court
wouldn't let you adopt me,

05:51.852 --> 05:53.312
you took me to see The Wiggles.

05:53.312 --> 05:55.022
And when I got my appendix out,

05:55.022 --> 05:56.857
you built me Dollhouse Manor.

05:56.857 --> 05:58.150
VICTOR:
Out of shoeboxes.

05:58.150 --> 05:59.818
[music stops]
JOSIE: Still kicked ass.

06:01.403 --> 06:04.364
Now a homemade lighthouse.

06:06.283 --> 06:07.868
So what's up?

06:10.162 --> 06:11.955
My God, are you smart.

06:15.876 --> 06:17.294
I'm...

06:18.462 --> 06:20.047
I'm worried
things might go wrong.

06:20.047 --> 06:22.299
Fights have been thrown
a thousand times.

06:24.927 --> 06:27.346
What would you do
if something happened to me?

06:28.514 --> 06:31.266
I mean, what wouldn't I do?

06:31.266 --> 06:33.268
No curfew. No check-in calls.

06:33.268 --> 06:35.062
No "find my family" app,

06:35.062 --> 06:38.190
- which is, like, freedom.
- I'm serious.

06:39.399 --> 06:41.276
What would you do?

06:41.276 --> 06:43.195
For real?

06:43.195 --> 06:45.864
[plaintive music plays]

06:45.864 --> 06:47.658
[sighs]
I mean,

06:47.658 --> 06:50.911
it's-it's not "what would I do?"
It's "what could I do?"

06:52.329 --> 06:53.830
Nothing.

06:53.830 --> 06:55.415
You're my life.

06:55.415 --> 06:59.253
You saved me from fire,
from these thugs.

07:04.466 --> 07:06.468
Thank you for this.

07:08.011 --> 07:10.305
<i>Te quiero.</i>

07:16.436 --> 07:18.814
Why do you keep looking at me
like that?

07:25.904 --> 07:28.907
♪

07:55.142 --> 07:58.145
[somber music plays]

08:22.669 --> 08:24.046
[kisses]

08:25.088 --> 08:26.673
<i>Te quiero.</i>

08:34.181 --> 08:37.184
[dramatic music plays]

08:49.738 --> 08:51.156
Mm!

08:51.156 --> 08:54.701
You're wearing the shoes
that I got you. [chuckles]

08:54.701 --> 08:56.703
Well,
I hope that's all you brought.

08:56.703 --> 08:58.372
Yeah, no cash, no ID.

08:58.372 --> 09:01.333
- Here's the phone.
- Thanks.

09:02.543 --> 09:04.002
Sorry.

09:05.003 --> 09:07.005
I have to be certain.

09:09.007 --> 09:11.510
Well, no nervous perspiration.

09:11.510 --> 09:14.513
No rapid heartbeat.

09:14.513 --> 09:17.266
Hmm. You accepted my offer

09:17.266 --> 09:19.476
within hours
of it being presented.

09:19.476 --> 09:21.061
Most people take a day or two

09:21.061 --> 09:23.689
before agreeing
to a life-and-death engagement.

09:23.689 --> 09:25.983
[chuckles]
But you're not scared.

09:25.983 --> 09:28.652
I'm terrified,
like before every fight.

09:30.487 --> 09:32.281
I just don't let it affect me.

09:32.281 --> 09:35.367
Because
you're a true scrapper.

09:35.367 --> 09:37.953
It's why I was so pleased
when you called.

09:37.953 --> 09:40.289
As the conductor
of this orchestra,

09:40.289 --> 09:44.001
I, of course, am not allowed
to wage on the outcome,

09:44.001 --> 09:47.129
but if I could,
I'd bet my last dollar on you.

09:47.129 --> 09:48.714
- People bet on this?
- Yes.

09:48.714 --> 09:50.591
Prescreened
and approved participants

09:50.591 --> 09:52.843
bet on how many hours
you'll last,

09:52.843 --> 09:55.762
which hunter might kill you,
where it might happen.

09:55.762 --> 09:58.557
Whether you kill the hunter
and, if so, which one.

09:58.557 --> 10:00.642
We have investors who support

10:00.642 --> 10:01.977
and train your pursuers

10:01.977 --> 10:03.896
like a nation does
an Olympic team.

10:03.896 --> 10:06.732
Some hunters are just so wealthy

10:06.732 --> 10:10.110
that this game's
the only thing left in life

10:10.110 --> 10:12.529
that makes them feel anything.

10:12.529 --> 10:14.656
- You're sick.
- No.

10:14.656 --> 10:17.201
I'm just managing a game.

10:17.201 --> 10:19.203
A game which starts

10:19.203 --> 10:21.246
at 5:53,

10:21.246 --> 10:23.415
which is just under a minute.

10:23.415 --> 10:25.918
The hunters
are all within 100 yards

10:25.918 --> 10:27.753
of the stadium.

10:27.753 --> 10:29.713
Don't forget this.

10:29.713 --> 10:32.257
You have
a one-minute head start.

10:32.257 --> 10:34.468
It used to be three,
but the competition committee

10:34.468 --> 10:36.178
felt it was too long.

10:37.179 --> 10:40.557
Underdogs sometimes win, Victor.

10:40.557 --> 10:41.767
Remember that.

10:41.767 --> 10:44.853
[tense music plays]

10:46.688 --> 10:48.607
[phone chimes]

10:48.607 --> 10:51.151
Welcome to the big leagues.
[beeping]
